title: Walt Whitman to Ellen M. O'Connor, 15 September 1889
text: CamdenP M Sept: 15 '89Enclosed I send Wm's picture given by him to me when last here—not knowing whether you have one like it, or w'd wish to use it, or favor it—But it is the one I like best— Of course I want it return'd to me here without fail—Have you rec'd the "Liberty" Boston, dated Sept. 7?—I requested one sent you at North Perry a week ago—If not reach'd you get one in Boston—there is a good memoriam of dear W (by Horace Traubel)—Nothing new or significant particular with me—I continue pretty poorly & uncomfortable brain, eyesight & viscera—half-clear & warmish here, after the week's storm—Sir Edwin Arnold, the English poet, was here to see me, very cheery & eulogistic—aged ab't 40, quite a traveler, now bound (soon) to the Pacific & round the world—I enclose you a picture or two besides—the one in the hat I call "the laughing philosopher"—I am sitting here alone in my big ratan arm chair in my den—Supper soon—I only eat two meals (no dinner) but relish them—Walt Whitman Walt Whitman to Ellen M. O'Connor, 15 September 1889
